 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">1</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">The system is set up with some large energy mismatch \delta {\rm{\Omega }}\gtrsim {\kappa }_{+}. This ensures a slow relaxation to the steady state once the primary mode drive is turned on, the relevant rates being {{\rm{\Gamma }}}_{\pm }\sim {({\kappa }_{+}/B)}^{2}{\tau }_{{\rm{m}}}^{-1}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">2</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">With the driving turned off, G = 0, the mechanics are prepared in their initial state. As discussed in section, 2: #njpaa6206s2, the auxiliary mode remains at zero population in the absence of driving. This corresponds to the spin pointing along {{\bf{e}}}_{z}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">3</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">We then ramp up the primary mode drive semi-adiabatically, until G\gg \delta {\rm{\Omega }}. In the spin language, we increase the Bx component until the effective field is nearly parallel with {{\bf{e}}}_{x}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">4</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">If the driving is increased sufficiently slowly, the spin itself will track the direction of the field and finally point along {{\bf{e}}}_{x}. We make use of the separation of scales to ramp over a time {t}_{\mathrm{ramp}} such that \begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;{B}^{-1}\ll {\kappa }_{+}^{-1}\ll {t}_{\mathrm{ramp}}\ll {\tau }_{\mathrm{meas}}.\end{eqnarray} \end{align*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\tag{ B1 }</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\end{equation*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="o">5</subfield>
  <subfield code="m">Finally, we perform a homodyne measurement as described in section, 4: #njpaa6206s4. Here we use the estimator \begin{equation*} \begin{align*} \begin{eqnarray}&amp;&amp;{\hat{n}}_{b}^{\mathrm{meas}}(t)\equiv {\left[\sqrt{\tfrac{2{g}^{2}}{\kappa }}\right]}^{-1}\cdot \left(\displaystyle \frac{1}{t}{\int }_{0}^{t}{\rm{d}}\tau {\hat{X}}_{\mathrm{out}}^{\pi /2}(\tau )\right).\end{eqnarray} \end{align*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\tag{ B2 }</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
 <datafield tag="999" ind1="C" ind2="5">
  <subfield code="m">\end{equation*}</subfield>
  <subfield code="9">refextract</subfield>
 </datafield>
